So this is the reasoning behind the code. We as familiars can claim to be stalkers. If we stalk somebody who has visited somebody that died, we can claim stalker and present the incriminating information (for example, a wolf who somebody). Claiming stalker does put a familiar out into the open and into danger, so we want to reduce the amount of familars out in the open as much as possible. This is why familiars encode a message of whom their target visited during the day, so that the familars who claimed stalker can share the information, even the info of other familars who haven't claimed.
I suggest all familiars always send their encoded message, even if it doesn't seem valuable, or if you plan to go public with your info anyway. Just as a rule.
The message is as follows: your first message (the text before a line break) has the same amount of letters as the listing of that person. So Danny = 1, HeatherChandler = 2, Emcee = 3, etc...
If we all have said who we're stalking during the night, we can see who that person visited by looking at the amount of letters in your first message.
There is one exception to be caught: if you're redirected by a Succubus, should there be one.
In that case, your first message will be some personal 'good morning'-style message, which we can identify as a signal 'hey, i've been redirected'
The message you send afterwards encodes who you've been redirected to: in this case, we count the amount of syllabes in the message to see who you've been redirected to
the message thereafter encodes who that person visited; the code is done in the usual manner (amount of letters = listing)
I hope this clears things up.
